<center>
<h2>Issues '96: The Candidate's Briefing Book</h2>
<b><A HREF="/heritage">The Heritage Foundation</a></b>
</center><p>
<h3>Chapter 16</h3>
<center><h2>DEFENDING AMERICA</h2> 

<CITE><B>By <a href="/heritage/staff/moore.html">Thomas G. Moore</a>, <a href="/heritage/staff/spring.htm">Baker Spring</a>, and <a href="/heritage/staff/hillen.html">John Hillen</a> 
</B></CITE>
</center>
<p>
<a href="#NAT"><B>National Security, Military Strategy And The Defense Budget</B></a>
<p>
<a href="#MAIN"><B>Maintaining A Quality Fighting Force</B></a>
<p>
<a href="chpt16.html#EXP"><b>Experts</b></a>         


<P>U.S. defense policy is undergoing its most sweeping  reappraisal since World
War II. The defense budget has dropped every  year for ten years, and from the
end of FY 1988 through FY 1995,  the Pentagon has eliminated well over one
million military  personnel. Nevertheless, despite the shrinking of America's
military might,  it is not yet clear how weak America can afford to become, or 
indeed what the major mission of the U.S. armed forces will be in the  21st
century.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The most dangerous threat to America today is the proliferation  of
long-range nuclear missiles that could reach American soil  from Iran, Iraq,
North Korea, or some other hostile nation.  Intelligence officials state that at
least 20 countries already have or may  be developing both weapons of mass
destruction (including  nuclear weapons) and ballistic missile delivery 
systems.<A HREF="ftnt16.htm#1">1</A>  While no Third World
countries yet have ballistic missiles with sufficient range  to reach the United
States, it is a virtual certainty that some will  have them by the next decade.
Yet America has no defense against  these weapons. Strategic anti-missile
defenses are more important  than ever and could be deployed by the early part
of the coming  century. To do otherwise -- to leave America undefended against such a clear physical threat -- would be a dereliction of duty with  tragic
potential consequences.
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 2 --> 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Other possible near-term threats to U.S. vital national interests  are the
potential re-establishment of an expansionist dictatorship  in Russia, military
expansionism by Iran or Iraq, attacks by  North Korea against South Korea, or
militarily threatening moves  by China against Taiwan. A defense posture capable
of  countering these threats can be maintained at far less cost than the Cold 
War demanded. However, the Clinton Administration is not  maintaining these
necessary defenses. Instead, it has presided over a  period of decline and
confusion in America's military capabilities.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<a name="NAT"><CENTER><H2>NATIONAL SECURITY, MILITARY STRATEGY, AND THE DEFENSE BUDGET
</B></H2>
<P>
<A HREF="chpt16.html#ISSUES">The Issues</A> | <A HREF="chpt16.html#FACTS">The Facts</A> |  <A HREF="chpt16.html#RECORD">The Record</A> | <A HREF="chpt16.html#Q&A">Q&amp;A</A>
</CENTER><p>
<a href="def_am_1.gif">Table 1</a>: Department of Defense Budget Authority

<P><B><A NAME="ISSUES">THE ISSUES
</A></B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P>There are many national security issues and questions  dividing liberals
from conservatives, but not all are familiar. What, for  example, is the right
amount to spend on defense now that the  Soviet threat has ended?  There is no
consensus on the Left or the  Right; much of the old Left-Right division on
defense strategy and  spending ended with the fall of the Soviet Union. Many 
conservatives want to focus entirely on domestic problems and cut all  federal
spending, including defense. Many liberals (including the  Clinton
Administration), while not supporting higher defense  spending, want to use
American military forces in humanitarian,  peacekeeping, and non-traditional
missions which put enormous pressure  on the shrinking defense budget.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>There are many other issues and questions facing the  candidates this year:
What is the proper use of American military force in  the 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 3 -->  post-Cold War world, and what kind
of forces are needed?   Should the U.S. military be converted to a kind of
global  peacekeeping constabulary?  Or should the armed services continue to
focus  on their traditional role of deterring threats to America's vital 
interests, the central element of which is preparing to fight and  win wars?  If
the U.S. military is to maintain its focus on this  traditional warfighting
role, what level of personnel is needed, and  how should the armed forces be
organized, trained, and equipped  for the future?
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The post-Cold War world can be characterized as an &quot;Age  of Chaos.&quot;
 While the Soviet Union has fallen and no longer  threatens the free world with
nuclear annihilation, new conflicts have  been spawned  ethnic, tribal, and
religious  between emerging  nations and at the sub-national level. Some of
these conflicts  may threaten U.S. interests; most will not. But they certainly 
disturb peace and order in the world. Under what circumstances should  the U.S.
intervene?  What are sound and politically supportable  criteria for the use of
American military force abroad?  These are  two key questions facing the U.S.
today.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The U.S. armed forces are not merely subordinate to civilian  leadership,
starting with the Commander in Chief, but highly  responsive, precisely because
of their command hierarchy. How  should the military respond to the social and
political agenda of the  President and his Administration?  Should the
Administration use  this highly responsive institution to foster revolutionary
social  change or as a laboratory for social experimentation?  What is the 
impact on combat readiness when radical social changes are forced on  the armed
forces?
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 4 --> 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Perhaps the most contentious unresolved defense issue is  this: Should the
American homeland be defended against the  growing threat of long-range
ballistic missiles and the proliferation   especially among potentially hostile
nations  of weapons of mass  destruction?  Five years after the Gulf War, in
which the  largest single loss of American lives came from an Iraqi Scud missile
 attack, the U.S. still has no better defense against regional or  theater
missile threats than the <U>Patriot</U> missile, which was designed  primarily
not as a missile defense, but as an anti-aircraft missile.  The question is:
Should the U.S. move aggressively to deploy  more effective theater missile
defenses for U.S. forces and allies abroad?   Or should America continue to rely
on arms control treaties  like the 1972 Anti-Ballistic Missile Treaty to protect
its security? 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><A NAME="FACTS">THE FACTS</A></B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B>*</B>     The budget (in spending authority) for the
Defense  Department reached its peak in FY 1985. Today, it is being cut sharply 
despite instability and threats to America's security around the world.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*</B>     In constant, inflation-adjusted dollars, there was a decline
of  35 percent in defense spending from FY 1986 to FY 1995. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*</B>     President Clinton proposes to slash budget authority for the 
Department of Defense from $282 billion to $276.6 billion by  the year 2002. In
constant, inflation-adjusted dollars, this would  represent another cut of about
24 percent in defense spending from  the FY 1992 baseline.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*</B>     President Clinton's defense budget fails to fund his own 
defense program. The Heritage Foundation calculates that projected  spend
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 5 -->  ing in the President's five-year
defense plan (FY 1996 - FY  2000) will fall short by $110 billion. Other
organizations, including  the Congressional Budget Office, the Center for
Strategic and  International Studies, the Defense Budget Project, and the
General  Accounting Office, concur that the Clinton Administration  is
underfunding its own defense program.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*</B>     The Reagan defense buildup in the 1980s increased active  Army
divisions from 16 to 18 and reserve divisions from 8 to 10 by  FY 1986.
Clinton's defense plan would cut these forces roughly  in half, reducing active
Army divisions to 10 and reserve  division equivalents to somewhat more than 5.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*</B>     The Air Force reached a high during the Reagan years of 26 
active tactical wings and 13 reserve wings. Clinton would cut  these forces by
about half, to 13 active and 7 reserve wings.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*</B>     The Marine Corps during the Reagan years reached a high  of
199,000 active-duty Marines and 42,000 reservists. Clinton  proposes
approximately 174,000 active-duty and 42,000 reserve  personnel.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*</B>     In addition, Ronald Reagan increased total Navy ships from 479
 to a high of 569 and the number of aircraft carrier battle groups to  15.
Clinton would reduce these levels by about 40 percent, to  346 ships and 11
aircraft carrier battle groups.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*</B>     The Clinton Administration proposed a budget for missile 
defense that is less than half of what the Bush Administration proposed  for the
five-year period covering FY 1995-FY 1999.
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 6 --> 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*</B>     A general readiness crisis precipitated by the Clinton defense
 budget was highlighted in two separate congressional  reports.<A
HREF="ftnt16.htm#2">2</A>  These reports noted that many
front-line American combat units  were understrength and forced to cancel
critical training, strip  other units for spare parts, and deploy on missions at
80-90  percent strength. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*</B>     A General Accounting Office report on the effect of 
peacekeeping operations on combat capability concluded that it could take up  to
18 months to retrain a division on peacekeeping duty for  combat.<A
HREF="ftnt16.htm#3">3</A>  This means that the U.S. Army in
Europe, most of which is  deployed in support of the Bosnian peace
implementation mission,  is effectively out of the warfighting business for from
two to  three years.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*</B>     A March 1995 report by the CIA's Nonproliferation Center 
entitled <I>The Weapons Proliferation</I><U> 
</U><I>Threat </I>states that at least 20 Third World countries either are
developing or already have  ballistic missiles.
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><A NAME="RECORD">THE RECORD</A></B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The Clinton Administration has all but abandoned strategic  ballistic
missile defense (BMD). What is left of the nation's BMD  program is both
misdirected and underfunded. The  Administration's current plan directs the bulk
of funds toward defenses  against short-range ballistic missiles, ignoring the
need to defend  U.S. territory against long-range ballistic missiles. It reduces
the  budget for missile defense by almost $23 billion  more than 50 percent  
from FY 1995 through FY 1999. Even the plan's  high-priority &quot;theater&quot;
defenses against short-range missiles are cut by $4.5  bil
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 7 -->  lion over the same period.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The Clinton Administration is providing neither the resources  nor the
proper direction in maintaining strong conventional  forces. Instead of
identifying specific national interests and the threats  to them, the
Administration has formulated a vague strategy of  &quot;engagement and
enlargement&quot; that confuses the purposes of  national security policy. In
its national security planning, the  Administration has placed far too much
emphasis on tangential issues  like domestic economic policy, environmental
policy, and foreign  economic development.<A
HREF="ftnt16.htm#4">4</A>  The result has been a national
security  planning process out of control  one disconnected not only from  the
Administration's decision-making process, but also from the  hard realities of
the threats America faces.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The current National Security Strategy developed by the  Clinton
Administration fails to make clear where and under what  circumstances U.S.
forces may be asked to fight. While the Clinton  Administration has established
some guidelines for military  intervention, for example, it ignored many of them
in its decision to  send troops to Bosnia. In Bosnia, the Administration made
the  mistake of creating a vital American interest where there otherwise  would
not be one. By promising U.S. troops in a yet-to-be-defined  mission and putting
American credibility on the line during the  Dayton peace talks, the Clinton
Administration presented  Congress with the choice of supporting the
Administration or damaging  U.S. credibility by breaking its word. The risks of
the Bosnian  intervention clearly are out of proportion to the costs, and the
exit  strategy is essentially an exit date of a year or less after the 
intervention began. Most controversial of all, however, was President  Clinton's
decision to deploy American forces without congressional  ap
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 8 -->  proval or public support. Public
opinion supporting the  intervention crested at 40 percent in December 1995,
when the House  of Representatives passed a resolution condemning the Bosnia 
mission. At the same time, the Senate expressed only lukewarm  support  support
directed at American forces, but not the  Clinton policies.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Another example of poor defense leadership by the  Administration was its
1993 &quot;Bottom-Up Review&quot; of U.S. military forces.  The purpose of the
BUR was to devise a new military force to  implement U.S. strategy in the
post-Cold War era. In meeting this  goal, however, the BUR failed. The Clinton
Administration promised  to maintain sufficient military forces to fight and win
two  medium regional conflicts, but the forces provided for by the 
Administration strategy are clearly inadequate for a two-war scenario. 
President Clinton's proposed defense budgets for the period  covering FY 1996 to
FY 2000 are not enough to pay for the BUR  force, according to numerous defense
analyses, including those of  The Heritage Foundation and the General Accounting
 Office.<A HREF="ftnt16.htm#5">5</A>  The Pentagon will be
around $110 billion short over five years if  it pursues the current Clinton
Administration defense spending plan. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P> Deploying the forces proposed for a single major conflict from  the other
services would leave virtually nothing in reserve if a  second major conflict
began. Of the total active force of 11 aircraft  carrier battle groups proposed
for the Navy, for example, the Clinton  Administration would assign four to five
carriers to each of the  two major regional conflicts, leaving perilously little
room for error.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Even worse, because &quot;peace operations&quot; will draw from the  &quot;same
collection of general purpose forces&quot; already obligated for  major 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 9 -->  regional contingencies, the
Administration intends to support  them by committing up to two Army divisions,
one Marine brigade,  two aircraft carrier battle groups, and two Air Force wings
from  an already overcommitted force.<A HREF="ftnt16.htm#6">6</A>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The bottom line: At the same time the Clinton Administration  has been
cutting the size and readiness of U.S. forces, it has been  increasing the
commitments they are supposed to cover. In  other words, the President is
developing a military &quot;strategy&quot;  whose reach exceeds its grasp and
which inevitably will leave some  vital U.S. interests undefended.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Because of Clinton's mismanagement of U.S. defense policy,  the U.S. could
not repeat the<B> </B>sweeping victory of the Persian Gulf  War today<B>.</B>
The Persian Gulf War epitomizes U.S. military  prowess. The forces that won
Desert Storm were largely the product of  the Reagan Administration's military
buildup during the early  1980s. But the Clinton Administration is sacrificing
the combat  readiness of the force of tomorrow to preserve operational readiness
 today. Had Ronald Reagan and Congress done this in the 1980s,  George Bush
could not have won such a decisive and relatively  low-casualty victory in the
Persian Gulf. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>President Clinton and Congress owe the same careful  stewardship to the next
President. Not only has Clinton reduced the  armed forces to the point where
they lack the means to fight and win  a Gulf War (while maintaining a minimum of
other defense  commitments), but his budget cuts have severely affected the 
combat readiness of this reduced force. For instance, some Marine  divisions are
operating at 80-90 percent of their assigned  combat strength, Army combat
battalions assigned to be the first forces  in 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 10 -->  the Persian Gulf have been forced
to cancel annual gunnery  training, and Navy fighter squadrons have been forced
to  cannibalize some units in order to keep others  flying.<A
HREF="ftnt16.htm#7">7</A>  These types of readiness crises
threaten to make the U.S. military a hollow  fighting force.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>WHAT TO DO IN 1997</B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>To avoid further critical weakening of America's combat  capability, there
are several actions that the next Administration and  Congress must take.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*     Devise a coherent national military strategy.</B> In addition to 
providing adequate resources, Congress and the next Administration  need to
devise a new military strategy for the U.S.; for all intents  and purposes,
America now has none. U.S. defense policy should  be built on four fundamental
strategies:
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B>Strategy #1:</B> Selective Engagement. The United States
has  global interests. In fact, it has economic and political interests in 
practically all regions of the world. But it does not have security  interests
in all parts of the world. When it comes to employing  U.S. military power,
America has to make choices. It should choose  to engage its armed forces
primarily in ways that affect the  global balance of power. The main purpose of
American military  power should be to establish a balance of power favorable to 
American and Western interests in key regions of the world  Europe,  Asia, and
the Persian Gulf. According to this strategy, the U.S.  would bear the principal
responsibility for the collective defense of  these regions, while U.S. allies
in the regions affected would  become responsible primarily for collective
security, peacekeeping,  and 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 11 -->  settling lesser conflicts that
are essentially regional in nature.  It must be emphasized that selective
engagement is a military  strategy, not a national strategy encompassing all
aspects  (economic, political, and diplomatic) of U.S. policy. Moreover,
selective  engagement implies that America needs a military force capable  of
handling core missions in different regions of the world.  These forces should
not be customized for specific regions when  undertaking peacekeeping and other
missions short of war.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Strategy #2:</B> Dissuasion. The U.S. armed forces should be  strong
enough to dissuade other nations from attempting to threaten  the U.S., its
interests, and its allies. By forcing them to recognize  the futility of
aggression, such power even may discourage  potential enemy nations from
substantially arming themselves. To have  the desired deterrent effect, this
power must be global in reach  and capable, when necessary, of achieving
decisive military  victory over most potential enemies.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Strategy #3:</B> Strategic Defense. With many potentially  unstable
regimes acquiring both nuclear weapons and long-range  ballistic missile
delivery systems, anti-ballistic missile defenses are  absolutely essential to
defense of the U.S. homeland.  Threatening nuclear retaliation to deter an
attack using these weapons may  fail with any one of these regimes. The ability
to knock out single  or multiple missile launches could save tens of millions of
 American lives and spare the country unimaginable devastation.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Strategy #4:</B> Force Projection. With many potential trouble  spots
around the globe, U.S. forces need to be redesigned so they can  be deployed
quickly around the globe. With U.S. bases  overseas shrinking in number, America
increasingly will have to be able  to 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 12 -->  project force overseas from its
own territory. Thus, the U.S.  needs a strong navy, flexible expeditionary
forces, and an army  capable of decisively defeating a large and modern force on
the battlefield.
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P>In addition to reflecting these four fundamental strategies, a  sound and
credible U.S. defense policy must:
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*     Acknowledge that the Clinton Administration's Bottom-Up  Review
force is not adequate to fight and win two medium-size  regional conflicts
simultaneously,</B> but should be postured to  fight and win simultaneously one
major regional conflict and  one smaller contingency. If the Administration's
objective is to  win two major regional conflicts simultaneously, it must
provide  a larger force  and the budget and other resources to sustain  that
force.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*     Budget approximately $285 billion per year</B> (with annual 
adjustments as needed for inflation) for defense from FY 1997  through FY 2001.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*     Devote adequate funds to research and development</B> so  that
tomorrow's force will have the advanced weaponry needed to  win with as few
casualties as possible. The research and  development account should be
increased to $38 billion (1995 dollars) by  the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*     Increase military pay to keep pace with inflation.</B> This will 
ensure that high-quality personnel continue to serve in the  all-volunteer
military.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*     Maintain spending for operations, maintenance, and training</B> 
at 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 13 -->  1995 levels, adjusted for
inflation. This funding is essential to  keep the U.S. armed forces fully
trained and combat ready.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*     Restore adequate funds to crippled ballistic missile defense 
programs.</B> In FY 1997 the Pentagon should spend about $1.2  billion more on
missile defenses than the $3 billion the Clinton  Administration is likely to
request. Thus, the total, which includes funds  for the Ballistic Missile
Defense Organization (BMDO) and a  few select programs under the Air Force
budget, should be about  $4.3 billion to $4.5 billion in FY 1997.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*     Develop a cheaper but more effective approach to missile  defense.</B>
Sea-based and space-based systems, rather than relatively  ineffective and
costly ground-based ones, would fill the bill. The  best architecture would be
one based on accelerating the Navy's  &quot;Upper Tier&quot; missile defense
system and then moving to deploy  a combination of space-based interceptors and
space-based  lasers early in the next decade.<A
HREF="ftnt16.htm#8">8</A>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*     Keep an eye on the future.</B> The computer chip and 
microelectronics revolutions are bringing about a corresponding revolution  in
military affairs. As its forces shrink, the U.S. must maintain  the most
technologically advanced military in the world, paying  close attention to new
operational concepts made possible by new  technologies  in particular,
information warfare capabilities,  improvements in surveillance and
precision-strike weapons, and  advanced &quot;situational awareness&quot; of
battlefield commanders.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><A NAME="Q&A">Q &amp; A</A></B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Q. Don't we spend enough on defense?  The Cold War is  over; 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 14 -->  why can't we get by with
dramatically smaller military forces?
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>A.</B> American forces already are smaller than during the Cold  War,
and they continue to shrink in size. The Pentagon has cut  more than one million
personnel during the drawdown after the end  of the Cold War. But though the
Cold War threat has ended,  the world is entering an era of new threats and
conflicts, some  of which are very dangerous. America's security and prosperity 
still depend upon a military large enough and capable enough to  defend vital
U.S. interests around the globe. For that force to remain  sufficiently combat
ready and technologically advanced to deter or  defeat future threats, the
nation must invest in adequate resources.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Q. Critics of missile defense say that no rogue state can threaten  us
with missiles today. Why do you insist on hyping the threat  from ballistic
missiles?
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>A.</B> Ballistic missile technology is now 50 years old and is  no
longer high technology. More countries are acquiring ballistic  missiles and
missile technology and using these destructive  weapons once they obtain them.
Ballistic missiles have been used in the  war in Afghanistan, the Iran-Iraq War,
the civil war in Yemen, and  the Persian Gulf War. In the Gulf War, more
Americans (28)  died from missile attack than from any other enemy action when 
an Iraqi Scud fell on a U.S. barracks in Dharan. Inevitably,  these rogue states
will acquire missiles with greater ranges and  increased accuracy. Fielding
comprehensive defenses against the  emerging missile threat will take some 10
years; if the U.S. waits until  rogue states actually deploy missiles with
ranges sufficient to reach  U.S. territory, it will be too late. Finally, U.S.
territory is at risk  today because of intercontinental ballistic missiles
(ICBMs) and  subma
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 15 -->  rine-launched ballistic missiles
(SLBMs) deployed by China  and Russia. At a minimum, the U.S. should deploy
defenses to  address the possibility of unauthorized or accidental missile
launches  by these two countries. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Q. Some critics say there is no readiness crisis in the military.  Is
there a crisis in readiness or not? 
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>A.</B> Former Assistant Secretary of Defense Lawrence J. Korb,  a
scholar at the Brookings Institution, argues that there is no  readiness crisis.<A
HREF="ftnt16.htm#9">9</A>  However, two separate reports
based on the  evidence from field units themselves paint a dramatically
different  picture. Senator John McCain's <I>Going Hollow: The Warnings of the 
Chiefs of Staff</I> and Representative Floyd Spence's 
<I>Military Readiness: The View from the Field</I> document how funding
shortfalls  have forced understrength first-line combat units to cancel
training,  curtail missions, and cease flying in preparation for eventual 
military missions. At the same time, Clinton has sent the military on 
humanitarian missions to Bosnia, Somalia, Haiti, Rwanda, and  elsewhere at the
expense of combat readiness.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Q. What should be done about the inability of the Bottom-Up  Review
Force to fight and win two simultaneous major conflicts?
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>A.</B> Create a &quot;one-and-a-half-war&quot; fighting force. The size
of  the U.S. forces needed depends on the magnitude of the  commitments made to
meet possible threats. It is unlikely that the U.S. will  face more than one
large-scale regional conflict similar to the  Persian Gulf War at any one time
over the next five years.  Conceivably, however, the nation may have to deal
with one small-scale  regional conflict roughly the size of the 1989 Panama
operation  con
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 16 -->  currently with a large-scale
conflict. The U.S. should maintain  a one-and-a-half-war force capable of
engaging in such  conflicts simultaneously.<A
HREF="ftnt16.htm#10">10</A>  While this strategy accepts a
higher level of  risk than the Clinton Administration's &quot;two war&quot;
strategy,  the Administration's defense budget puts the nation in a  position
where it will have barely enough forces to fight one major  regional conflict by
itself. The important thing is to stop the  demobilization process now. If the
nation later finds it necessary, it should  re-examine the two-war strategy and
increase the defense budget  accordingly.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Q. How many and what kinds of conventional forces and  equipment does
the nation need?
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>A.</B> The U.S. needs a Navy of about 400 ships, with 12 active 
aircraft carriers. The Marine Corps should retain three Marine  Expeditionary
Forces (MEFs), which would require 177,000  active-duty Marines; the Marine
Corps Reserve should number 42,000.  The Navy and Marine Corps Reserve,
therefore, should be reduced  by a smaller proportion than the other services.
Also needed are  fast sealift ships and new heavy airlifters, like the C-17, to
replace  the nation's rapidly aging airlift fleet and maintain the ability to 
get heavy forces into a theater of conflict in a hurry. Finally,  adequate
pre-positioned stocks of heavy equipment, either ashore near  likely trouble
spots or on maritime pre-positioned ships, are essential  to sustain a conflict
for more than a few weeks.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Q. Won't building strategic defenses kill arms control?
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>A.</B> The U.S. should carry out the strategic nuclear weapons 
reductions agreed upon with Moscow. This would lessen the  Russian 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 17 -->  nuclear threat while leaving the
U.S. with the forces it needs  both to protect itself should a political
reversal take place in  Moscow and to deter such lesser nuclear powers as China.
At the  same time, however, a policy of nuclear deterrence will be inadequate 
in a world where many nations possess both weapons of mass  destruction and
long-range delivery systems. With many  potentially unstable, even irrational,
regimes capable of delivering  nuclear weapons, strategic anti-missile defenses
are more essential  than ever. The Cold War policy of deliberate vulnerability
to  missile attack is unthinkable in this new international climate.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Building missile defenses will not kill arms control.  Ronald Reagan signed
numerous arms reduction deals with the  Soviets while pursuing the Strategic
Defense Initiative (SDI). It would  be no different in the future. The Russians'
bluster against U.S.  strategic defense comes simply from their desire to keep
America  vulnerable to their strategic missiles, in which they have made such  a
huge investment, and which constitute their one surviving  qualification as a
global power. The U.S. should offer to discuss a  transition from an
offense-only posture to missile defenses by  both sides, but Russia should not
be permitted a veto over the  deployment of U.S. missile defenses.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Q. What should be done about the ABM Treaty?
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>A.</B> The U.S. should terminate the 1972 Anti-Ballistic  Missile (ABM)
Treaty. The treaty effectively bars the deployment of  effective,
non-threatening defenses. A new multilateral  agreement with all relevant
parties to provide for the mutual deployment  of such defenses should be
pursued.<A HREF="ftnt16.htm#11">11</A>
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 18 --> 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Q. Should the U.S. military be reorganized to deal mainly  with
peacekeeping operations and not large wars, which are things  of the past?
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>A.</B> The U.S. military exists for one principal reason: to fight  and
win America's wars. Under no circumstances can it fail in  that most profound
task. Given the many American security  commitments around the globe, the U.S.
military must train  continuously and arduously towards this goal. During the
Cold War, the  U.S. military concentrated almost exclusively on decisive 
battlefield engagements against the forces of the Soviet Union and the  Warsaw
Pact. It was this training and focus that gave America the  military prowess to
defeat Iraq so completely in the Persian Gulf  War. Such a commitment to winning
in combat must not be  squandered through continuous commitment to peacekeeping
operations or  a restructuring of vital combat units for such missions. The 
deployments to Somalia, Haiti, and Bosnia already have greatly  reduced the
combat capabilities of the military. Any further dilution of  this fundamental
mission stands to put the U.S. military in a  position similar to the one it
faced in Korea in 1950. At that time,  American occupation forces were untrained
for combat and nearly  wiped out by the North Korean invasion. America cannot
afford to  lose on the battlefield, and history conclusively proves that 
concentrating on military missions other than war increases the possibility  of
such a disaster. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B> Q. When should the U.S. support or participate in U.N.  peacekeeping
operations?
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>A.</B> Only when it serves U.S. national interests. There are  many
humanitarian crises in the world, but neither the U.S. nor the  U.N. 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 19 -->  has the resources to deal with
every one. When America does  participate, U.S. troops must remain under U.S. or
allied, rather  than U.N., command. A peacekeeping mission must have clear 
command and control arrangements, adequate force, appropriate  criteria for
success, a definite endpoint, and a plan for  disengagement once success is
achieved. As a rule, U.S. military forces  should engage in allied combat
operations when their employment is  decisive, unique, and make the difference
between success and failure.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<center><a name="MAIN"><H2>MAINTAINING A QUALITY FIGHTING FORCE
</H2></center>
<center><A HREF="chpt16.html#ISSUES2">The Issues</A> | <A HREF="chpt16.html#FACTS2">The Facts</A> |  <A HREF="chpt16.html#RECORD2">The Record</A> | <A HREF="chpt16.html#Q&A2">Q&amp;A</A>
</center>

<P>

<P><B><A NAME="ISSUES2">THE ISSUES
</A></B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The U.S. military exists for one principal reason: to fight and  win the
nation's wars. But an effective military force depends on  more than weapons,
equipment, and adequate defense budgets.  Such intangible human factors as
leadership, esprit de corps,  morale, mutual trust, and unit cohesion are as
vital to an effective  combat force as the material factors. These intangible
elements make  up the &quot;warrior ethos&quot; that is needed if U.S. armed
forces are to  win America's wars.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>This ethos is under siege. The Clinton Administration has tried  to put
homosexuals in the military and women in combat  positions. This agenda of
political correctness will undermine the  combat effectiveness of U.S. forces if
allowed to continue unchecked. It  is eroding morale and corroding the mutual
trust that must exist in  an effective fighting organization.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>The goal of this agenda is to re-create the military services in  a 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 20 -->  fashionable, liberal image.
Liberal social activists who exercise  an inordinate influence on the Clinton
Administration view the  military as a federally sponsored vehicle for social 
experimentation. Because they see it as the last bastion of &quot;male
domination,&quot;  liberals want to de-masculinize the military regardless of
the effect  on its capacity to do its only job, which is to fight and win 
America's wars. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Because the military is a command hierarchy, liberal social  activists
believe they can impose their agenda from the top down.  Most service members
oppose social engineering of this kind  because they know it saps the fighting
power of the services, and thus  exposes them to greater danger. But they are
intimidated from  speaking out, and often find their careers in jeopardy if they
do not  embrace the &quot;diversity&quot; agenda imposed on them from above.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><A NAME="FACTS2">THE FACTS</A></B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE><P><B>*</B>     Former Chairman of the Joint Chiefs General Colin
Powell,  all serving Chiefs of Staff, and most former members of the  Joint
Chiefs have stated unequivocally that acknowledged  homosexuals in the
military's ranks are harmful to the good order and  discipline of the services.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*</B>      Women currently make up approximately 12 percent of the  U.S.
armed forces, more than any other nation's military. While  women do not serve
in so-called direct combat positions in the  infantry, armored, or field
artillery units, many are being assigned to  combat support units, combatant
ships, and pilot billets which put  them in harm's way. These assignments
inevitably would put women  in combat during a war.
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 21 --> 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*</B>     During the Persian Gulf War, American women soldiers  were
taken prisoner for the first time in U.S. history. These women  were sexually
abused by Iraqi captors. The possibility that women  prisoners will be raped and
tortured, or that large numbers of  women will be killed and wounded in action,
could have a  dramatically negative effect on American public opinion and on the
 nation's ability to prosecute a war. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*</B>     No other nation places women in combat posts, not even 
Israel, despite a common misconception to the contrary and even  though Israel
has a manpower shortage. Israel used women in combat  for a short time during
its war of independence and made it  policy never to do so again except in the
most dire national  emergencies. In the Israel Defense Force, women do receive
basic combat  training and may be attached to combat units in support roles, but
 they do not take part in combat operations. (Recently, the Israeli  Supreme
Court directed the Israeli armed forces to permit a  woman to train as a combat
pilot; she has since dropped out of flight  training.) Other nations, such as
Denmark, allow women to serve  in combat units but also note that they are not
likely to see combat.  In any event, Denmark concedes that its policy was
undertaken  to satisfy contemporary social mores and could hurt unit  cohesion
and combat readiness. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>*</B>     Introducing women into all combat specialties means creating 
two different standards in order to account for the physiological  differences
between women and men. A combat unit's effectiveness  is predicated on unit
cohesion, which is based in turn on the bonds  of trust among soldiers in a
unit. Training to two different  standards is the surest way to wreck unit
morale, raising problems of  favorit
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 22 -->  ism and of training that does not
meet the standard required by  the mission.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Putting women in combat units degrades combat readiness.  For instance,
pregnant women are not able to deploy on military  missions with their units,
causing further problems of morale,  unit cohesion, and readiness. The aircraft
carrier USS Eisenhower  is the first U.S. naval ship to try to integrate men and
women. In  the first six months of a recent deployment, 14 women on  the
Eisenhower became pregnant while on cruise, and were freed  from their duties.
The message sent to sailors is that there are  different standards for men and
women, standards that are based not on  the capability of the individual to help
the team win in combat, but  on one's sex.
</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><A NAME="RECORD2">THE RECORD</A></B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>President Clinton has instituted policies that would put women  in combat
and homosexuals in the military. Because the  President comes from an
aggressively anti-military background, these  decisions as Commander in Chief
have been resisted by the  American military establishment.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>For example, on April 28, 1993, the Clinton Administration  announced that
the Department of Defense would open certain  combat aviation positions to
women. This change in policy affected  all three services and made women
available for duty in all  aviation units, including air cavalry units in the
Army. Women  currently are barred only from direct participation in infantry,
armor,  and some artillery units.
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 23 --> 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Moreover, early in his Administration, the President revoked  the
long-standing military ban on homosexuals, establishing instead  a fuzzy &quot;don't
ask, don't tell&quot; policy that simply prohibits open  displays of
homosexuality. This policy is a poor compromise  between the President and the
Joint Chiefs of Staff, who were  concerned about the adverse impact of lifting
the ban. It makes it  technically legal for homosexuals to serve in the armed
forces, but also  allows them to be discharged for openly displaying homosexual 
behavior. As might be expected from such an ambiguous compromise,  the policy
has been challenged in several court cases but with  unclear results, being
upheld in some decisions and struck down in  others. Congress has hidden behind
the compromise language, refusing  to hold hearings or conduct proper oversight
of Defense  Department regulations implementing the law prohibiting open 
homosexuals from serving, as passed in the FY 1995 Defense authorization bill. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P> President Clinton also objected to provisions in the 1996  Defense
authorization bill that allow the military to  discharge servicemembers
diagnosed with HIV, the virus that causes  AIDS. This ban was imposed because
HIV-positive  servicemembers could infect other members in combat operations.
This is in  keeping with existing military policy that prevents the deployment 
of servicemembers with other contagious or debilitating  diseases. President
Clinton maintains that this discriminates against  HIV-positive personnel; the
Department of Defense maintains that  because HIV-positive servicemembers cannot
serve on  deployments, they should not continue to serve while others must
deploy in  their place. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>WHAT TO DO IN 1997
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 24 --> 
</B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>To ensure that the U.S. military continues to do its job of  fighting and
winning America's wars, the Administration and  Congress should:
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>-     Return to the Chiefs of Staff the power to determine social 
policies based on the requirement to fight and win in combat.</B> The  service
Chiefs are charged by law to provide the best military advice to  the President
and Secretary of Defense, and the best command  guidance to their respective
services. They have a heavy  responsibility and must be allowed to put the
nation's defense needs and  the combat capabilities of the services ahead of the
political  pressures or passing social agendas of the moment.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>-     Eliminate the Defense Advisory Committee on Women in the  Service.</B>
This committee was set up after the Korean War to advise  the Chiefs of Staff on
women's issues in the service. Over the  years, however, it has become a vehicle
for promoting the  legislative agendas of militant homosexual lobbies, feminist 
organizations, and other liberal pressure groups. In addition, similar 
organizations in the services should be focused on the challenge of  maintaining
equality and professionalism in the military while promoting  the warrior ethos
and military ethic among all members of the  service. They should not advance
the radical agendas of groups who  view the military as &quot;just another job&quot;
and believe it needs to be  restructured so its values and ethics are in line
with those of  contemporary society.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>-     Ensure that the military oversight committees of Congress  protect
the careers of loyal service officers who properly advise  against the social
engineering agenda.</B> For instance, congressional  oversight  which includes
final approval of military promotion lists   
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 25 -->  must ensure that exemplary
officers like Commander  Robert Stumpf, U.S. Navy, are not ridden out of the
service as the  result of a political correctness witch hunt. Commander Stumpf,
a  Naval aviator and former commander of the Navy's precision  combat flying
team, was denied promotion because he attended the  notorious Tailhook
convention in 1991. Even though a Navy  investigation completely exonerated him
of any connection with the  events of Tailhook, Commander Stumpf was denied
promotion by a  Senate Armed Services Committee policy that the Navy notify  the
committee of all officers who attended the Tailhook  convention. Such egregious
bows to political correctness are nonsensical,  unjust, and damaging to morale.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>-     Abandon the confusing &quot;don't ask, don't tell&quot; policy 
regarding homosexuals in the military.</B> This policy is a clear example of  a
President who wants to have his cake and eat it too. As a result,  the policy is
under legal challenge in two different courts and  most likely will need to be
settled by the Supreme Court. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B><A NAME="Q&A2">Q &amp; A</A></B>
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Q. Why should the services ban women from combat and  homosexuals from
military service?
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>A.</B> Advocates of women in combat and homosexuals in the  military
view military service as similar to any other job and  assume that gender or
sexual orientation are insignificant in the  military environment. They are
wrong. Combat is a team endeavor and  the most demanding environment 
physically, mentally, and  morally  that one can endure. It is not a &quot;job&quot;
but a life-and-death  under
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 26 -->  taking. The primary criterion for
inclusion must be the ability  of the individual to enhance  not to detract from
 the  effectiveness of the unit. A military organization functions best when 
differences among individuals in a unit are minimized. That is why  soldiers are
required to look, act, dress, and train alike. It makes  no sense to break down
all of these differences only to inject  the greatest difference of all 
individual sexual identity  into a unit.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Professional military judgment and experience indicate that  mixing known
homosexuals with heterosexuals undermines  cohesion and combat effectiveness.
Common sense suggests that men  and women distract each other even when trying
not to do so. In  combat, such distractions can be the difference between life
and  death. The purpose of the military is to build the most effective  fighting
force to defeat an enemy as quickly, and with as few  American casualties, as
possible. Differences in sexual identity will  weaken discipline and
effectiveness, thus making it more difficult to  prevail in combat.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>Access to the military has never been based on what is &quot;fair.&quot;  
Military service is a privilege and sometimes a duty, but never  a right.
Because victories in combat are achieved by cohesive  units, the armed forces
routinely sacrifice individual interests to  ensure unit cohesion. Military
service is legally restricted or denied  to patriotic Americans who are too
tall, too short, too fat,  color-blind, flat-footed, or mentally or physically
handicapped. This is no  reflection on the inherent worth of these individuals;
they simply  do not meet the military's needs.<A
HREF="ftnt16.htm#12">12</A>  For the same reason,  women
should be barred from combat and known homosexuals should  be excluded entirely
from military service.
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 27 --> 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Q. Before the military was desegregated in 1948, many of  the same
arguments used today to oppose gays in the military  were used to oppose blacks
in the service. Can't America's GIs learn  to live and work with homosexuals in
the same way they learned  to live and work with black Americans?
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>A.</B> As General Powell  himself a black man  has explained,  being
black is a benign condition, a matter of birth. On the  other hand, homosexual
activity is not. It is a gross fallacy to equate  the two. Moreover, black
Americans have proven themselves on  the field of battle and in every other
military function. They  have made remarkable contributions to the military and
to the  nation's security, and are recognized universally among the best 
soldiers, sailors, Marines, and airmen in the world. On the other hand,  the
open acceptance of homosexuality in the ranks almost  always causes problems of
morale and discipline.
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>Q. If a woman can perform the same job as a man, why  can't women hold
combat jobs?  To limit women to support roles  also limits their career
opportunities for advancement in the military.
</B></P>
<P>
</P>
<P><B>A.</B> The fundamental purpose of military service is to  defend
America, not to advance careers. There can be only one  standard for a warrior,
and that is determined by what it takes to fight  and win in combat. The great
majority of women in the military,  and even some men, cannot meet the physical
standards required  for service in combat units. Having different standards for
men  and women would ruin morale and unit cohesion. Putting women  in combat
also would raise a host of thorny questions, among  them: How will the
inevitable formation of male-female special  relationships affect discipline and
unit cohesion, which are essential  to 
<!-- Generation of PM publication page 28 -->  success in combat?  How can a
woman's privacy be respected  adequately in combat conditions?  What would be
the effect  on troops and the impact on public support for a combat mission if 
a number of females were taken prisoner and abused by their  captors or
exploited for psychological warfare or propaganda advantage?   How would
official and legal efforts to prevent sexual  harassment of women prevent the
rise of double standards and the  inevitable breakdown of morale and unit
cohesion?
<p>
