&quot;direct-action&quot; groups such as Greenpeace and People for 
the Ethical Treatment of Animals (PETA).  These 
groups received $4.07 million in 1994over 11 percent of 
corporate public affairs giving.
<P>Tables I and II show corporations that earned the 
best and worst ratings in this year's <I>Patterns of 
Corporate Philanthropy</I> based on their public-policy giving.  
These ratings have also been translated into letter grades.  
Yet even corporations with the most market-oriented 
giving earned grades of only &quot;B&quot; and &quot;C&quot;.
<P><B>Health Care and the Environment</B>
<P>We identified 28 public-policy organizations that 
received at least $250,000 in corporate funding in 1994.  
As Table III shows, we classified 21 of these as<BR>
